This is how I would answer it tomorrow.

Notice the structure:

Customer → Business → Risk → Decision


---

> I would start by understanding the objective.

The fintech is optimizing for conversion, while the bank is optimizing for customer trust and informed consent. My responsibility is to find the right balance rather than automatically choosing one side.

First, I would analyze the funnel to determine where customers are dropping off. Are they abandoning because the process is genuinely complex, or because the value proposition is unclear?

Second, I would evaluate which steps are essential for informed consent and which are creating unnecessary friction. For example, I would be reluctant to remove visibility into what data is being shared or for how long, because those are fundamental elements of customer control.

Third, I would explore alternative designs that simplify the experience without reducing transparency. Examples might include clearer language, progressive disclosure, better UX, pre-selected options with clear explanations, or streamlined authentication.

I would also run controlled experiments and measure both conversion rates and customer trust metrics.

Ultimately, my goal would not be to maximize clicks. In Open Banking, consent is not a compliance checkbox; it is the foundation of customer trust. I would support simplification if customers remain informed and in control of their data.




---

If the MD asks the follow-up

> Simplified consent increases conversion by 35%, but complaints about unexpected data sharing increase by 20%. Which metric matters more?



A strong answer:

> Neither metric should be viewed in isolation.

The increase in conversion demonstrates business value, but the increase in complaints suggests customers may not fully understand what they are consenting to.

In Open Banking, trust is difficult to earn and easy to lose. A short-term increase in conversions can create long-term damage if customers feel surprised by how their data is being used.

My preference would be to identify the root cause of the complaints and redesign the consent experience to preserve most of the conversion gains while improving customer understanding.

If I had to choose between maximizing conversion and preserving informed consent, I would prioritize informed consent because sustainable growth depends on customer trust.




